{"cursor":"5384","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\nA 'dispersion' is a system in which particles are dispersed in a continuous\nphase of a different composition (or state). See also emulsion. A dispersion is\nclassified in a number of different ways, including how large the particles are\nin relation to the particles of the continuous phase, whether or not\nprecipitation occurs, and the presence of Brownian motion.\n\nThere are three main types of dispersions: *Coarse dispersion (Suspension)\n*Colloid *Solution\n","linknr":180,"url":"Dispersion_(chemistry)","recorded":1362553150,"links":28,"instances":["element","chemistry","colloid","chemistry","chemistry","chemistry"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Colloidal chemistry","Solutions","Chemical mixtures"],"headings":["Types of dispersions","Structure and Properties of Dispersions","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ac/Chem_template.svg/32px-Chem_template.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["precipitation","chemistry"],["suspension","chemistry"],["sol","colloid"],["suspension","chemistry"],["amalgam","chemistry"],["mercury","element"],["interface","chemistry"]],"members":["mercury","amalgam","sol","interface","precipitation","suspension"],"related":["Emulsion","Precipitation_(chemistry)","Brownian_motion","Suspension_(chemistry)","Colloid","Solution","Nanometer","Micrometer","Gas","Air","Oxygen","Nitrogen","Liquid","Aerosol","Fog","Mist","Vapor","Hair_spray","Solid","Smoke","Cloud","Particulate","Dust","Solution","Water","Foam","Whipped_cream","Shaving_cream","Alcoholic_beverage","Emulsion","Miniemulsion","Microemulsion","Milk","Mayonnaise","Hand_cream","Sugar","So